    type: string
    description: Full name of the authorized signatory signing for the employer
    display_label: Employer Signatory Name
    section: Parties
  - name: employer_signatory_title
    type: string
    description: Title of the authorized signatory signing for the employer
    display_label: Employer Signatory Title
    section: Parties
  - name: employee_name
    type: string
    description: Full legal name of the employee
    display_label: Employee
    section: Parties
  - name: employee_title
    type: string
    description: Employee job title or position (optional)
    display_label: Employee Title / Position
    default: ''
    section: Parties
  - name: effective_date
    type: date
    description: >-
      Effective date of this agreement — the date the last party signs. It
      anchors the durations stated in Cover Terms.
    display_label: Effective Date
    section: Timing
  - name: governing_law
    type: string
    description: Governing law state
    display_label: Governing Law
    section: Legal
    default: Arkansas
  - name: confidentiality_trade_secret_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of confidentiality obligations for trade secrets
    display_label: Trade Secrets Duration
    default: Perpetual
    section: Confidentiality
  - name: confidentiality_other_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of confidentiality obligations for non-trade-secret information
    display_label: Other Confidential Information Duration
    default: 24 months
    section: Confidentiality
    rationale_source: editorial
    default_value_rationale: >-
      24 months is common for non-trade-secret confidentiality obligations in
      employment agreements. Arkansas keeps confidentiality agreements on a
      different track from covenants about competition or competitive work, so a
      finite term on non-secret information is a common-law reasonableness
      choice.
  - name: employee_nonsolicit_included
    type: boolean
    description: Whether the employee non-solicitation covenant is included
    display_label: Employee Non-Solicitation Included
    default: true
    section: Employee Non-Solicitation
  - name: employee_nonsolicit_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of employee non-solicitation restriction
    display_label: Employee Non-Solicitation Duration
    default: 24 months
    section: Employee Non-Solicitation
    rationale_source: benchmark
    benchmark_ref: restrictive-covenant/employee-non-solicit-duration
    default_value_rationale: >-
      24 months matches the modal employee non-solicit term observed in benchmarked, publicly-filed
      employee agreements; 12 months is the common lighter alternative. Arkansas places agreements
      not to solicit, recruit, or hire employees outside the non-compete statute when they do not
      concern competition or competitive work, so this covenant is judged under common-law
      reasonableness and cannot borrow the statutory reformation or consideration rules.
  - name: covered_employee_period
    type: string
    description: >-
      Lookback period for determining which employees are covered by the
      non-solicitation restriction.
    display_label: Covered Employee Period
    default: 12 months
    section: Employee Non-Solicitation
    default_value_rationale: >-
      12 months is the most common lookback period for employee non-solicitation
      scope.
  - name: customer_nonsolicit_included
    type: boolean
    description: Whether the customer/partner non-solicitation covenant is included
    display_label: Customer Non-Solicitation Included
    default: true
    section: Customer Non-Solicitation
  - name: customer_nonsolicit_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of customer/partner non-solicitation restriction
    display_label: Customer Non-Solicitation Duration
    default: 12 months
    section: Customer Non-Solicitation
    rationale_source: legislation
    requirement_id: REQ-labor-and-employment-law.restrictive-covenant-agreement.arkansas.keep-restricted-period-within-two-year-presumption
    default_value_rationale: >-
      12 months sits within the two-year presumptively reasonable window. A
      customer non-solicit that concerns competitive work may be tested under
      the statutory framework, so its duration is kept inside the presumption.
  - name: covered_customer_period
    type: string
    description: >-
      Lookback period for determining which customers are covered by the
      non-solicitation and non-dealing restrictions.
    display_label: Covered Customer Period
    default: 12 months
    section: Customer Non-Solicitation
    rationale_source: editorial
    default_value_rationale: >-
      12 months is the most common lookback period for customer non-solicitation
      scope, and a specific customer group tied to the employee's contacts is an
      Arkansas reasonableness factor for tailoring a customer-facing restraint.
  - name: noncompete_included
    type: boolean
    description: >-
      Whether the non-competition covenant is included. Arkansas tests a
      non-compete by whether it is ancillary to the employment relationship,
      backed by a protectable business interest, and limited in time and scope no
      greater than necessary to defend that interest; this template recites the
      protectable-interest basis and biases the duration into the two-year
      presumptively reasonable window.
    display_label: Non-Competition Included
    default: false
    section: Non-Competition
    rationale_source: editorial
    default_value_rationale: >-
      Conservative default. Non-competes are the most heavily scrutinized
      covenant; include only after confirming a real protectable business
      interest, that the duration is within the two-year presumption, that the
      worker is not a physician whose right to practice within scope would be
      restricted, and that the worker does not hold a Title 17, Subtitle 3
      professional license that takes the covenant outside the statute.
  - name: noncompete_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of non-competition restriction
    display_label: Non-Competition Duration
    default: 12 months
    section: Non-Competition
    rationale_source: legislation
    requirement_id: REQ-labor-and-employment-law.restrictive-covenant-agreement.arkansas.keep-restricted-period-within-two-year-presumption
    default_value_rationale: >-
      12 months sits well inside the two-year presumptively reasonable window.
      Arkansas authority has recited the historical pattern that one- and
      two-year limits were upheld while three- and five-year limits were
      unreasonable, so the tool defaults short.
  - name: territory
    type: string
    description: >-
      Geographic scope of the non-competition restriction. Arkansas law does not
      treat a missing geographic restriction as automatically overbroad if time
      and scope remain no greater than necessary; where geography is stated, tie
      it to where the protected interest is actually at risk.
    display_label: Restricted Territory
    default: the geographic area in which Employee provided services or had material customer contact
    section: Non-Competition
    rationale_source: legislation
    requirement_id: REQ-labor-and-employment-law.restrictive-covenant-agreement.arkansas.pair-missing-geography-with-customer-or-activity-limits
    default_value_rationale: >-
      Tied to the employee's actual service and contact area. A defined territory
      should track where the protected interest is at risk; where no geography is
      stated, Arkansas law shifts the limiting burden onto the customer and
      activity scope, which this template supplies.
  - name: competitive_business_definition
    type: string
    description: >-
      Description of the business activities that constitute competition with
      the employer.
    display_label: Competitive Business
    section: Non-Competition
  - name: specified_competitors
    type: string
    description: >-
      Optional named list of specific competitors. Limiting the restriction to a
      specific group of entities associated with the employer's business is an
      Arkansas reasonableness factor and strengthens enforceability.
    display_label: Specified Competitors
    default: ''
    section: Non-Competition
    rationale_source: editorial
    default_value_rationale: >-
      Empty by default because named-competitor limits are deal-specific. When
      supplied, naming a specific competitor group can strengthen tailoring by
      limiting the restraint to entities connected to the employer's business.
  - name: nondealing_included
    type: boolean
    description: Whether the no-business-with-covered-customers covenant is included.
    display_label: No Business with Covered Customers Included
    default: false
    section: No Business with Covered Customers
  - name: nondealing_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of the no-business-with-covered-customers restriction
    display_label: No Business with Covered Customers Duration
    default: 12 months
    section: No Business with Covered Customers
    rationale_source: legislation
    requirement_id: REQ-labor-and-employment-law.restrictive-covenant-agreement.arkansas.keep-restricted-period-within-two-year-presumption
    default_value_rationale: >-
      12 months sits within the two-year presumption. Non-dealing restrains
      competitive work even when the customer calls first, so it is drawn to the
      statutory tailoring test.
  - name: passive_public_holdings_threshold
    type: string
    description: >-
      Maximum ownership percentage of publicly traded securities permitted under
      the Passive Public Holdings carveout.
    display_label: Passive Public Holdings Threshold
    default: five percent
    rationale_source: benchmark
    benchmark_ref: restrictive-covenant/passive-ownership-carveout
    section: Definitions
    default_value_rationale: >-
      Five percent of any class of publicly traded securities is the modal
      passive-investment carve-out threshold observed in benchmarked, publicly-filed
      employee agreements that include the carve-out (lower 1-3 percent thresholds are
      the common tighter alternatives). A clause that forbids ordinary public shares
      restrains conduct that threatens no protectable interest, exactly the excess width
      an Arkansas court would trim.
  - name: noninvestment_included
    type: boolean
    description: Whether the non-investment covenant is included.
    display_label: Non-Investment Included
    default: false
    section: Non-Investment
  - name: noninvestment_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of non-investment restriction
    display_label: Non-Investment Duration
    default: 12 months
    section: Non-Investment
    rationale_source: legislation
    requirement_id: REQ-labor-and-employment-law.restrictive-covenant-agreement.arkansas.keep-restricted-period-within-two-year-presumption
    default_value_rationale: >-
      12 months sits within the two-year presumption. An active-ownership
      investment restraint functions as a non-compete and is drawn to the same
      statutory tailoring test.
  - name: nondisparagement_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of non-disparagement obligation (measured from termination)
    display_label: Non-Disparagement Duration
    default: 24 months
    section: Non-Disparagement
    default_value_rationale: 24 months is common for employment non-disparagement provisions.
priority_fields:
  - employer_name
  - employee_name
